21. Pro Deum fidem, Sto. [Pythias aloud to herself, coming sarward] Terence is wonderfully happy in the conduct of the play, by contriving that Pythias should always retain the same animosity against Parmeno, and that Parmeno, by all he says, should still more provoke Pythias3 for this is what leads to the unravelling of the plot. These masterly strokes, says Donatus, are designed for the learned and skilled in

criticism; the rest for the common herd of spectatorS.— 22. Quid ’

est ? Pythias resolved to be revenged of Parmeno, for the trick he had played them, contrives to appear surprised, and under great concern for what was doing within. This naturally startles Parmeno, and

” makes him impatient to know what is the matter. Pythias, upon this, devises a story on purpose to frighten him, and does it so effec- tually, that in his fear, not knowing what to do better, -he resolves to discover all to the old man, in which Pythias encourages him, because her resentment is not yet over, and she wishes to torment him still further. — 23.
